(Bonus Challenge: Python List vs Singly Linked List) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(If the helpdesk performs thousands of searches per day but only a few insertions and) Tj
T*
(deletions, a Python list is generally more appropriate than a singly linked list.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Both a Python list and a singly linked list have O\(n\) worst-case linear search when) Tj
T*
(searching by ticket ID without an index. However, Python lists store references in a) Tj
T*
(contiguous array, so scanning them is usually faster in practice because nearby elements are) Tj
T*
(loaded efficiently by the CPU cache. A linked list requires pointer chasing from node to) Tj
T*
(node, and each node may be stored in a different memory location. That pattern causes more) Tj
T*
(cache misses and slower real-world traversal.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Python lists also avoid per-node pointer overhead. A linked list node stores ticket data) Tj
T*
(plus an extra next pointer, and each node is separately allocated. A Python list uses one) Tj
T*
(contiguous block of references to ticket objects, which tends to reduce allocation overhead) Tj
T*
(and improve memory access behavior. Therefore, for search-heavy workloads with few) Tj
T*
(structural changes, the Python list is usually the better practical choice.) Tj
T*
ET
